To all those people that want to use your midi device in this android app. Just download the free trial pc version onto your pc. Then search for the midi mappings list for your midi mixer.then save this file onto your pc. Then simply move this file into the mappings folder on this android program and it should work. I have an old numark total control mixer and it would not work with this app until i followed these steps.. Now i can mix with my old mixer and kill the eq,search,load etc.

replyContent:
Hello Lee, 
- If you do not use them, deactivate the Keylock and Quantize features
- You can pre-analyse your library (tap 'Analyse' in the library, top right). It's a CPU intensive task, and it's better if done before you start your mix.
- If you're using a Samsung device: Go to the advanced settings and switch the ""OpenSL mode"" to ""Async""

Fun to mess around with but it's basically mixing without headphones. There is no way to mix in tracks without both sides putting out sound at the same time. For instance, when you mix with turntables or cdjs, there are channels for the headphones so you can only hear one song at a time or mixed together, separate from what is being played in the speakers. This app just has it all on one channel, forcing the dj to either pre-cue tracks, or just drop the track in and let it ride using the sync button. replyContent: Hi, you can actually pre-cue but for this you will need a split cable for the audio, we actually have two output modes dedicated to doing this. No dj app offers split output without a cable so this isn't any different from anyone else. We are also looking into the Mixcloud issue.

Audio apps on Android are tough. Mixvibes has made a decent app for casual mixing. Slightly annoying that while there is SoundCloud account integration it doesn't work if you use Google accounts to sign into soundcloud. Midi support is only for a few controllers. It would be much better to allow generic midi mapping and then allow the community to share those mappings. Documentation isn't great; seems mostly focused on forums and FAQ; a wiki would be better. The app is a little buggy; not for professionals.
It's not absolutely perfect but definitely close. Personally, I would add the ability to loop more precisely; may be by adding a snap control similar to FLStudio's pattern section.
It has more than what I expected. It's definitely worth it.

You just have to dig through your "File Explorer" app until you find the Cross DJ folder under Android Data. .

content: When a track is playing, and I go to load up another track on the other deck, there is a slight 'crunch' sound and lag. This is picked when recording. Any ideas for a fix?
replyContent:
Hi, 
- Close every other app while using Cross DJ
- If you do not use them, deactivate the Keylock and Quantize features
- You can pre-analyse your library (tap 'Analyse' in the library, top right). It's a CPU intensive task, and it's better if done before you start your mix.
- Turning Wi-Fi / Bluetooth off save battery.

I never could be arsed to carry around all my stuff and was always jealous about all the iPad fanboys having all their gear pretty simple in some excellent apps out there. However, Cross DJ is pretty much the tool. Grab a simple USB-powered boombox, a battery-powered cross-mixer and off you go! Thanks guys, it's what I was looking for. Definitely worth the money. There are a few quirks though, especially how it handles the id3-tags of MP3s. A lot of MP3s I own are from a multi-CD collection and hence have the same title and album, but a different Disc number. Although it can sort the titles accorindg to the track number, you end up with all titles from the same collection interleaved. So sorting according to disc number would be excellent. Also, sometimes is totally wrong with the length calculation of tracks, if you have the same song with the same title from different artists. Example: I go the song "Rise (Italian Edit)" by Eddie Amador, and then "Rise (Gambafreaks radio edit)" by Club Sounds. Eddie's edit is 4:47 and the other 3:55. However, they get displayed as 21:26 and 16:35. Also there seems to be some kind of looping involved. Is that a cuepoint/looping artefact?

It's amazing that what used to require a laptop (and controller for my preference) is now possible with just my cell phone (and a splitter cable for my preference).  Most of what I was doing was a blind run, some songs were analyzed (and loaded great), but the ones that weren't ready did take a  little bit to load, but did eventually get ready with bpm to go. Load times were always devastating in VDJ w/Notebook, and my Galaxy S2 (Yes, S2) runs about as well (on CM11 Nightly, so YMMV).  At this point I pretty much only mix UK Hardcore, so 87.5 BPM detection are not uncommon (and I do appreciate the "BPMx2" function very much because of it). The layout, once you get the hang of it, does work quite well (and it runs without issues on the DPI setting on 120, a BIG PLUS in my book since I like my text tiny).  The only thing I can really knock points for is the occasional hickup. I'm certain closing background apps and turning off data/wifi would help immensely, but I was stressing my little phone, and it hung in there, even UNDER MINIMUM specs.  Even with the snag, we had a great time, and I got to mix some awesome tunes with just my phone, and that's worth 5 stars in my book. ‚ò∫

replyContent:
Hi Taylor, 
You can actually change the tempo after it is set : 
- PITCH: Move the pitch fader (on tablet), or go up from the jog's center and circle around (mobile)
- PITCH-BEND: Go left or right from the jog's center
- RESET TEMPO: Double tap on the jog's center
Concerning the hot cues, be sure that our designers + engineers are looking into it.

David, this is an awesome feedback. Thanks!
(And if you want to improve the latency, be sure that Quantize mode is off. In fact, when Quantize mode is on, the app adds the offset to the beat to perform actions like cue point triggers. However, it is useful when you want to jump seamlessly within the track, with no audible cut.)

content: Pretty decent first version on my Nexus 10. Occasional pops and clicks, hopefully will be solved in future releases. One major problem here: The pitch control slider controls go from -100% to +100%, which makes them pretty much useless... there is an option in the Settings to change them to 2%, 4% or 8% but changing the value here does not have any effect unfortunately. Is this a bug or am I overlooking something obvious?
replyContent:
Thanks for your feedback, the dev. & design team is looking into it.
About the pitch setting: It is not a bug. What you can change is the pitch-bend value (different from the pitch value). Pitch bending is what you do when you want to slightly adjust the tempo of a track. To pitch bend in Cross DJ, swipe left or right from the jog-wheel's center.

Indeed, you cannot access the tracks bought in Google Play Music directly in Cross DJ.
It is the same for any other application: it is a Google limitation, probably justified by copyrights issues.

Solution: download the tracks to your Mac/PC with Music Manager. Then, upload them to your Android device (e.g. with Android File Transfer).

Awesome first step.  Actually usable. Actually fun. Actually sounds good.	Few things i've found: - You can keep your finger on the xy pad, switch the view mode, and continue to change the FX with that finger until you release, and can change anything in the new view with your other finger(s). Great if you want to simultaneously FX + equalize, or set a loop, or something, even on the same deck, though you have do be nimble :) - Occasional volume spike when entering browse mode. Have notified team, they say they cant replicate it so it might just be me - Audio seems to come out my headphones and the phone speaker simultaneously? Again have notified team, say they cant replicate it.  Overall i DEFINITELY recommend this app, it's the first viable DJ app for android. The quantize and sync work really well and it's easy to use with low latency on a proper phone (nexus 5). Will recommend to friends. Excited to see how they improve going forward, would love - USB audio or at least mono monitoring - Labels on the XY for each effect so you see what parameters you're changing - Windowed mode to put left deck in FX and right deck in Loops or whatever - Secret Airhorn button (kidding)
Definitely a v1.0, but with amazing potential! It's a bit raw and still lacks several important features, but I can't stop jammin'... :)
This is a first for Android, as it plays flawlessly. So much potential can grow from this. Only needs both network audio out like wifi and bluetooth as well as usb and headphone.
